quran[12]{c,v,t}:
  33,9,"You who have attained to faith, remember God's blessings upon you when mighty armies massed against you. We sent a violent wind against them and hosts that you could not see. God sees all that you do"
  33,10,"When they came against you both from above you and from below you, your eyes rolled [with fear] and your hearts leapt up to your throats, and you entertained [ill] thoughts about God"
  33,11,There the faithful were put to the proof and they were shaken as if by an earthquake
  33,12,"The hypocrites and people with sickness in their hearts said, \"God and His Messenger have promised us nothing but delusions"
  33,13,"Others said, \"People of Yathrib, you cannot withstand [the enemy] here: so go back!\" Yet others asked leave of the Prophet, saying, \"Our houses are exposed and [defenceless].\" They were in truth not exposed: they only wished to flee"
  33,14,"If their town had been stormed, and they had been incited to sedition, they would have rebelled with little hesitation"
  33,15,"They had already vowed before God that they would never turn their backs: and a vow made to God must be answered for"
  33,16,"Say, \"Flight shall not avail you: if you manage to escape from death or killing, you will enjoy life only for a short while"
  33,17,"Say, \"Who is there to shield you from God if He wishes to harm you? If God wishes to show you mercy, who can prevent Him.\" Besides God they shall find none to protect them, and none to bring them succour"
  33,18,"God knows exactly who among you hold the others back, who say to their brethren, \"Come over to our side,\" and they seldom take part in the fighting"
  33,19,"Begrudging you all help, but when danger comes, you can see them looking at you with rolling eyes as if in their death throes; but once their fear has passed, they come to you and do glib-talking in their greed for wealth. Such men have no faith, so God has foiled their actions. This is indeed easy for God"
  33,20,"They thought the confederate tribes would never withdraw. Indeed, if the confederates should come again, they would prefer to be in the desert, among the Bedouins. There they would ask news of you [from a distance]. But if they were with you, they would take very little part in the fighting"